<br>
Take spell with a large mana cost, so that you can cast it only a few times <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (less than ten)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with a full mana bar.  Say, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summon Rod of Transvergence</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which costs 400 mana.<br>
<br>
Now, make sure your mana bar is full, and cast as many of that spell as you can.  If there are no fizzles, you will be able to cast that spell always and exactly the same number of times before you get the message <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Insufficient mana to cast that spell</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  If you count fizzles as half a cast, it will also work out to be the same number of casts, to within a half.<br>
<br>
If it <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>were</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> random, then there would be some variance, especially with such a small number of casts.  That is why you use a higher cost spell instead, a smaller cost spell you could cast a larger number of times, and the variance would be harder to observe.<br>
<br>
Likewise, it is best to demonstrate this using a spell which you are 200% specialization at.  Again, if there actually were a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;specialization roll,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> then you would expect to see the most variation when the difference between success and failure was the greatest.  But you will see no variation, except for fizzles.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Master ArchMage Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
